'''Cranborne Money''' is the common name given to the annual payment to Opposition parties in the UK [[House of Lords]] to help them with their costs. It is named after [[Robert Gascoyne-Cecil, 7th Marquess of Salisbury|Lord Cranborne]], who was the leader of the House of Lords when it was introduced on 27 November 1996.<ref>{{Cite Hansard|house=House of Lords |title=Financial Assistance To Oppositionparties |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/lords/1996-11-27/debates/5240436c-5c9c-40b3-be7b-5a0e1ca77706/FinancialAssistanceToOppositionparties |date=27 November 1996 |column_start=267 |column_end=272}}</ref> [[Short Money]] is its counterpart in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]].
==Annual allocations== {| class="wikitable" |+ Cranborne Money allocations ! &nbsp; ! 2009/10 !! 2013/14 |- | '''Conservative Party''' | align="right" | 474,927 | align="right" | - |- | '''Labour Party''' | align="right" | - | align="right" | 555,748 |- | '''Liberal Democrats''' | align="right" | 237,126 | align="right" | - |- | '''Cross bench peers''' | align="right" | 61,003 | align="right" | 71,770 |- | '''Total''' | align="right" | 726,988 | align="right" | 627,518 |}
In addition to the above funds, the salaries of the [[Leader of the Opposition (UK)|Leader of the Opposition]] and Opposition [[Chief Whip]] in the House of Lords (as of 2014 the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]) are also paid from public funds. In 2009/10 such payments amounted to £73,617 and £68,074 respectively.
