<sup>1</sup>During [[World War II]], [[Nazi Germany]] annexed territory or established [[reichskommissariat]]s which extended [[Paragraph 175|Germany's laws against same-sex sexual activity]] to those territories and reichskommissariats. Same-sex sexual activity was previously legalized in the following countries or territories before German annexation or establishment of reichskommissariats: [[Bas-Rhin]] ([[LGBT rights in France|legal in 1791]]), [[Belgium]] ([[LGBT rights in Belgium|legal in 1795]]), [[Province of Belluno|Belluno]] ([[LGBT rights in Italy|legal in 1890]]), [[Friuli-Venezia Giulia]] ([[LGBT rights in Italy|legal in 1890]]), [[Haut-Rhin]] ([[LGBT rights in France|legal in 1791]]), [[Luxembourg]] ([[LGBT rights in Luxembourg|legal in 1795]]), [[Moselle]] ([[LGBT rights in France|legal in 1791]]), [[Kingdom of the Netherlands|Netherlands]] ([[LGBT rights in the Netherlands|legal in 1811]]), [[Nord (French department)|Nord]] ([[LGBT rights in France|legal in 1791]]), [[Pas-de-Calais]] ([[LGBT rights in France|legal in 1791]]), [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]] ([[LGBT rights in Poland|legal in 1932]]), and [[Trentino-Alto Adige/Südtirol]] ([[LGBT rights in Italy|legal in 1890]]). All countries and territories listed that where annexed or established into reichskommissariats by Nazi Germany during World War II where restored as independent countries or reincorporated into their previous countries during or after the war and thus re-legalized same-sex sexual activity in those areas.
<br /><sup>2</sup>In May 1973, the [[Libyan Arab Republic]] annexed the [[Aouzou Strip]] from [[Chad]]. Libya's laws against same-sex sexual activity where thus extended to the annexed Aouzou Strip. In August 1987, during the [[Toyota War]] between the [[Great Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya]] and Chad, Aouzou fell to the Chadian forces, only to be repelled by an overwhelming Libyan counter-offensive. The Aouzou dispute was concluded on February 3, 1994, when the judges of the [[International Court of Justice]] by a majority of 16 to 1 decided that the Aouzou Strip belonged to Chad. Monitored by international observers, the withdrawal of Libyan troops from the Strip began on April 15, 1994, and was completed by May 10, 1994. The formal and final transfer of the Aouzou Strip from Libya to Chad took place on May 30, 1994, when the sides signed a joint declaration stating that the Libyan withdrawal had been effected.
<br /><sup>3</sup>Same-sex sexual activity was never criminalized in the following countries and territories: [[LGBT rights in Benin|Benin]], [[LGBT rights in Burkina Faso|Burkina Faso]], [[LGBT rights in Cambodia|Cambodia]] [[LGBT rights in the Central African Republic|Central African Republic]], [[LGBT rights in Chad|Chad]] (excluding [[Aouzou Strip]]), [[LGBT rights in France|Clipperton Island]], [[LGBT rights in the Republic of the Congo|Republic of the Congo]], [[LGBT rights in Côte d'Ivoire|Côte d'Ivoire]], [[LGBT rights in the Democratic Republic of the Congo|Democratic Republic of Congo]], [[LGBT rights in France|French Polynesia]], [[LGBT rights in France|French Southern and Antarctic Lands]], [[LGBT rights in Gabon|Gabon]], [[LGBT rights in Laos|Laos]], [[LGBT rights in Madagascar|Madagascar]], [[LGBT rights in Mali|Mali]], [[LGBT rights in France|Mayotte]], [[LGBT rights in France|New Caledonia]], [[LGBT rights in Niger|Niger]], [[LGBT rights in North Korea|North Korea]], [[LGBT rights in Rwanda|Rwanda]], [[LGBT rights in South Korea|South Korea]], [[LGBT rights in Vietnam|Vietnam]], and [[LGBT rights in France|Wallis and Futuna]]. Same-sex sexual activity had also never been criminalized in continent of [[Antarctica]].]]

During the Portuguese colonization of Brazil, homosexuality was illegal in the country between 1533 and 1830, due to the imposition of the Portuguese Penal Code, which was influenced by the British [[Buggery Act 1533]].<ref>[http://pensamentorevolucionario.blogspot.com/2009/10/legislacao-mundial-sobre.html British Buggery Act 1533 and Portuguese Penal Code 1533 {{pt icon}}]</ref>

In 1830, eight years after the end of the Portuguese domain, sodomy laws were eliminated from the new Penal Code of Brazil.<ref>[http://www.cadastronacionalmedico.org/noticia/136-A-legislacao-sobre-a-homossexuais-bissexuais-transgeneros-transexuais-e-travestis-.htm The Penal Code and the Homosexuality {{pt icon}}] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120729084320/http://www.cadastronacionalmedico.org/noticia/136-A-legislacao-sobre-a-homossexuais-bissexuais-transgeneros-transexuais-e-travestis-.htm |date=2012-07-29 }}</ref>

After the [[French overseas territories]] located in the [[Americas]], Brazil was the first country in the [[New World]] and [[Southern Hemisphere]] to legalize [[homosexuality]]. Today in [[South America]] only [[Guyana]], a former [[British Empire|British colony]], considers homosexuality illegal.<ref>[http://lesbianlife.about.com/od/lesbianactivism/f/IllegalGaySex.htm In South America only Guyana is anti-homosexual {{en icon}}]</ref>

Since 1985 the Federal Council of Medicine of Brazil does not consider homosexuality as [[deviant]].<ref>[http://www.gph.org.br/faq.asp Homosexuality is not a deviant - Federal Council of Medicine of Brazil {{pt icon}}] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706161114/http://www.gph.org.br/faq.asp |date=2011-07-06 }}</ref> In 1999, the Federal Council of [[Psychology]] published a [[Resolution (law)|resolution]] that has standardized the conduct of [[psychologist]]s face the question: "... psychologists did not collaborate with events or services proposing treatment and cure of homosexuality." In 1990, five years after Brazil removed homosexuality from its list of mental illnesses, the General Assembly of the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO), with headquarters in [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]], removed the homosexuality, in the [[International Classification of Diseases]] (ICD).<ref>[http://www.correiobraziliense.com.br/app/noticia182/2010/05/16/brasil,i=192631/HA+20+ANOS+A+OMS+TIROU+A+HOMOSSEXUALIDADE+DA+RELACAO+DE+DOENCAS+MENTAIS.shtml Homosexuality is not a deviant - Federal Council of Psychologists of Brazil {{pt icon}}]</ref>

