{{Refimprove|date=September 2013}} [[Image:Placa remença Amer.jpg|thumb|Plaque commemorating the 500th anniversary of the ''remences''' acceptance of King [[Ferdinand II of Aragon|Ferdinand II]]'s mediation between the ''remences'' and the feudal lords. (Located in [[Amer, Selva|Amer]] monastery, where the arbitration occurred.)]]
'''Remensa''' ([[Catalan language|Catalan]]: ''Remença'') was a Catalan mode of [[serf]]dom. Those who were serfs under this mode are properly ''pagesos de remença'' (''pagesos'' meaning "peasants"); they are often (though not quite correctly) referred to simply as ''remences'' (singular ''remença'').
The Catalan term ''remença'' derives from the [[Latin]] ''redementia'' and emphasizes the possibility of redemption from [[Slavery|servitude]].<ref>[http://www.elalmanaque.com/diciembre/15-12-eti.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040810164842/http://www.elalmanaque.com/diciembre/15-12-eti.htm |date=August 10, 2004 }}</ref>
The severity of this way of life led to rebellions by the remensa peasants in 1462 and 1485 known as the [[War of the Remences]]. After the second revolt, King [[Ferdinand II of Aragon]] issued the ''[[Sentencia de Guadalupe]]'' (1486), outlawing the more severe abuses of the oppressive [[evil customs]] and allowing remensa peasants to be redeemed by a payment of 60 [[Solidus (coin)#France|sous]] per household, leaving a rural society that was still [[feudalism|feudal]] in character, but significantly reformed.
