{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}} {{Use British English|date=August 2017}} {{Infobox Organization |name = Richardson Institute |image = Richardson_Institute_Logo.png |size = 200px |caption = |formation = 1959 |extinction = |type = [[Research institute]] |purpose = Researching and educating on the theme of [[Peace and conflict studies|peace studies]] |headquarters = [[Lancaster University]], Bailrigg, Lancaster, LA1 4YL, United Kingdom |membership = |leader_title = Director |leader_name = Simon Mabon |parent_organization = Department of Politics, Philosophy, and Religion |affiliations = |budget = |website = [//www.lancaster.ac.uk/fass/centres/richinst www.lancaster.ac.uk/fass/centres/richinst] |remarks = }}
The '''Richardson Institute for Peace Studies''' was the first [[Peace and conflict studies|peace & conflict]] research centre in the UK and one of the first in the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lancaster.ac.uk/ppr/research/research-centres/richardson-institute/ |title= Department of Politics, Philosophy, and Religion: Research Centres |accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> It is part of the Department of Politics, Philosophy, and Religion at [[Lancaster University]], where its members publish research, hold lectures and workshops, and run academic outreach programmes.
==History== The Richardson Institute began as an independent organisation, the '''Lancaster Peace Research Centre''', in the [[North of England]] in 1959.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?redir_esc=y&id=EBzxsURb4-cC&q=richardson+institute#v=snippet&q=richardson%20institute&f=false |work= Journal of Peace Research |title= Encyclopedia of Violence, Peace, and Conflict |accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://jpr.sagepub.com/content/51/2/145.full.pdf |work= Journal of Peace Research |title= Peace Research – Just the Study of War?|accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref> The Centre was incorporated first into the Politics Department at Lancaster University, and then in 1969 into a branch of the Conflict Research Society at the [[University of Kent]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conflictresearchsociety.org/history/ |title= The Conflict Research Society: History |accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://press-files.anu.edu.au/downloads/press/n1879/pdf/book.pdf?referer=1879 |title= War, Strategy, and History |accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref> There the Centre was renamed the '''Richardson Institute for Conflict and Peace Research''' in honour of the polymath and pacifist [[Lewis Fry Richardson]], and was moved to 158 North Gower St, London, which it shared with the [[Women’s Research and Resources Centre]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://archiveshub.ac.uk/data/gb106-7pac |title= Papers of Pat Caplan |accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref> During this time the Institute not only published academic papers, but also released an animated film about the nature of human communication in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://library.sl.nsw.gov.au/search~S2?/dAnimated+films./danimated+films/-3%2C-1%2C0%2CB/frameset&FF=danimated+films+united+states&7%2C%2C23 |work= State Library of New South Wales |title= Communicate or Else |accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref>
On 1 October 1978, with funding from the [[Joseph Rowntree Foundation]], the Institute returned to Lancaster University as an autonomous body of the Politics Department.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bisa.ac.uk/files/BISA%20News/Autumn_1978_Issue_9.pdf |work= British International Studies Association Newsletter |title= Autumn 1978, No.9 |accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref> There its activities diversified into undergraduate and postgraduate teaching, ultimately leading to the creation of a [[studentship]] in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alumni.lancs.ac.uk/document.doc?id=14 |work= Steps |title= Summer 2007 |accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref> Its early [[Minor (academic)|minor course]] in conflict & peace research proved particularly popular, and the Institute became renowned for lecturing in "unashamedly [[Behavioural sciences|behavioural]]" models of social science.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bisa.ac.uk/files/BISA%20News/Spring_1980_Issue_13.pdf |work= British International Studies Association Newsletter |title= Spring 1980 |accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref> In 1990 the members of the Institute consolidated their work by publishing ''A Reader in Peace Studies'', a basic text that became set reading for many introductory peace studies courses.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gmu.edu/programs/icar/ijps/vol3_1/Harris.htm |title= A Portrait of University Peace Studies in North America and Western Europe at the End of the Millennium |accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref> As a result of this new activity, the Institute was given the more general trade name of the '''Richardson Institute for Peace Studies'''.
As the Institute shared more of the Politics Department’s day-to-day teaching responsibilities, its other activities declined. With funding from the [[Arts and Humanities Research Council]], the Institute was re-launched in September 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://results.ref.ac.uk/DownloadFile/EnvironmentTemplate/PDF?subId=1764 |work= Research Excellence Framework 2014 |title= Lancaster University: Theology and Religious Studies |accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref> In 2013 it began the Richardson Institute Internship Programme, a year-long, multidisciplinary research placement with such partners as the [[Institute for Strategic Dialogue]] and the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]], and in 2016 it opened a course in the [[Political theology|political theology of peace]] as the first in a number of [[distance learning]] modules on positive politics. The Institute also hosts an annual peace lecture series and runs a film club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lancaster.ac.uk/fass/centres/richinst/ |title= www.lancaster.ac.uk/fass/centres/richinst |accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref> Its present aim is to become an international partner of choice for universities and to improve the public understanding of peace. Since 2012 the Institute has published on such diverse topics as [[Indo-Pak relations]], sexuality in the [[Anglican Church]], and maritime [[Cyberwarfare|cyber operations]], and the [[ESRC]] has rated its research as outstanding.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lancaster.ac.uk/ppr/research/research-centres/richardson-institute/#publications |title= Richardson Institute Publications |accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.research.lancs.ac.uk/portal/en/clippings/richardson-institute-research-rated-as-outstanding-by-the-esrc(336a53aa-b8e1-4a7e-aae9-c063dedce4a0).html |work= Lancaster University Research Directory |title= Richardson Institute Research Rated as 'Outstanding' by the ESRC |accessdate=20 June 2016}}</ref>
