'''''There Ain't no Black in the Union Jack''''' is a 1987 non-fiction book written by [[Paul Gilroy]].<ref>[http://www.press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/T/bo3620902.html The University of Chicago Press]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=wR8gqFFPSxgC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Google Books]</ref><ref>[http://rac.sagepub.com/content/29/4/97.extract Rac.sagepub.com]</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/05/opinion/05iht-edlamont.html The New York Times]</ref><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/book-review-still-aint-no-black-in-the-union-jack-the-black-atlantic-paul-gilroy-verso-1195-1466777.html The Independent]</ref>
==Overview== Gilroy examines the [[racial politics]] of the [[United Kingdom]]. In particular, he discusses anti-black racism in the United Kingdom. This work of Gilroy's remains quite controversial to many for his views on racial politics in the United Kingdom and for his views on race and ethnicity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/book-review-still-aint-no-black-in-the-union-jack-the-black-atlantic-paul-gilroy-verso-1195-1466777.html|title=BOOK REVIEW / Still ain't no black in the Union Jack: 'The Black|date=1993-12-11|work=The Independent|access-date=2017-03-30|language=en-GB}}</ref>
